clinical_study.brief_title: Healthy Volunteers Study of the Effects of Olanzapine and Ziprasidone
clinical_study.official_title: A Randomized Comparison of the Acute Effects of Olanzapine and Ziprasidone on Whole Body Insulin Sensitivity in Healthy Volunteers

brief_summary.textblock:
Primary Aim: To test the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone administration, in comparison to placebo, on insulin sensitivity in antipsychotic-naïve healthy young men, measured as whole-body dextrose infusion rates (mg/kg/min), hepatic glucose production (glucose rate of appearance [Ra]), primarily muscle glucose utilization (glucose rate of disappearance [Rd]), and adipose tissue related free fatty acid production (glycerol rate of appearance [Ra]).
We hypothesize that olanzapine, but not ziprasidone, will result in acute decreases in insulin sensitivity.
Secondary Aim: To test the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone on insulin signaling pathways in antipsychotic naïve healthy young men.
We hypothesize that olanzapine, but not ziprasidone, will result in acute alterations in insulin signaling.

primary_outcome.description: To evaluate, using a within-subject placebo-controlled comparison, the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone administration on insulin sensitivity in antipsychotic-naïve healthy young men, measured as whole-body dextrose infusion rates (mg/kg/min).

To evaluate, using a within-subject placebo-controlled comparison, the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone administration on insulin sensitivity in antipsychotic-naïve healthy young men, measured as hepatic glucose production (glucose rate of appearance [Ra]).

To evaluate, using a within-subject placebo-controlled comparison, the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone administration on insulin sensitivity in antipsychotic-naïve healthy young men, measured as primarily muscle glucose utilization (glucose rate of disappearance [Rd]).

To evaluate, using a within-subject placebo-controlled comparison, the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone administration on insulin sensitivity in antipsychotic-naïve healthy young men, measured as free fatty acid release (glycerol rate of appearance [Ra]).

criteria.textblock:
Inclusion Criteria:
- Males aged 18-45 years
- BMI approximately ≥ 25 and < 35
- insulin approximately ≥ 15 µU/ml or triglyceride approximately ≥ 130 mg/dl
Exclusion Criteria:
- Any DSM-IV Axis I diagnosis
- prisoners
- any serious medical disorder (i.e. metabolic diseases, type 1 or 2 diabetes mellitus, endocrine disease, coagulopathy, clinically significant anemia, acute infection)
- taking prescription medications
- non-sedentary lifestyle with > 3 hours of exercise per week

outcome.title: Whole Body Insulin Sensitivity
outcome.description: To evaluate, using a within-subject placebo-controlled comparison, the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone administration on insulin sensitivity in antipsychotic-naïve healthy young men, measured as whole-body dextrose infusion rates (mg/kg/min).
outcome.population: The analysis was per protocol and involved subjects who completed both a clamp that involved an injection of either olanzapine or ziprasidone, and a clamp that involved a placebo injection. Nine subjects did not complete a second clamp as they were lost to follow-up. This resulted in the analysis of 37 participants.

measure.title: Whole Body Insulin Sensitivity
measure.description: To evaluate, using a within-subject placebo-controlled comparison, the acute effects of olanzapine or ziprasidone administration on insulin sensitivity in antipsychotic-naïve healthy young men, measured as whole-body dextrose infusion rates (mg/kg/min).
measure.population: The analysis was per protocol and involved subjects who completed both a clamp that involved an injection of either olanzapine or ziprasidone, and a clamp that involved a placebo injection. Nine subjects did not complete a second clamp as they were lost to follow-up. This resulted in the analysis of 37 participants.

analysis.groups_desc: The hypothesis being tested is whether there is a significant effect of one or both antipsychotics on whole body insulin sensitivity. Sample size was calculated using power calculations to detect significant effects of treatment on insulin sensitivity. Drug assignment is a 2-level fixed factor (olanzapine vs ziprasidone) as is order (drug first vs placebo first). Baseline of the dependent variable as well as baseline DEXA total fat were entered into the model as covariates.
analysis.p_value_desc: This p-value corresponds to the two way interaction between time and order and is not adjusted for multiple comparisons. The a priori threshold for statistical significance is alpha equal to 0.05. There was no 3 way interaction.
analysis.method_desc: Repeated measures ANCOVA with time as the repeated measure, drug assignment as a fixed factor, and order as a fixed factor.

measure.population: The analysis was per protocol and involved subjects who completed both a clamp that involved an injection of either olanzapine or ziprasidone, and a clamp that involved a placebo injection. measure.units: % change from basal to insulin phase

analysis.groups_desc: The null hypothesis is that olanzapine and ziprasidone would result in acute decreases in insulin sensitivity compared to placebo at adipose tissue, which was measured by evaluating the rate of appearance of labeled glycerol. The alternative hypothesis is that olanzapine, but not ziprasidone, would result in acute decreases in insulin sensitivity compared to placebo at adipose tissue.
analysis.p_value_desc: This p-value corresponds to the 3 way interaction between time, drug (olanzapine vs ziprasidone), and order (drug first vs placebo first) and is not adjusted for multiple comparisons.
